# AI in Australia: Second Order Effects

In previous pieces I discussed how [Programmers aren't out of a job just yet](programming-in-the-age-of-abundance.html) and [the likely first order effects of AI on the Australian economy](2026-02-29_AI_in_Australia_—_First_Order_Effects.md).

Second order effects are inherently harder to predict, but here are some that seem likely.

## Housing Pressure

Australia’s housing system is already supply-constrained. Zoning, permitting, and infrastructure delays limit elasticity. If those constraints remain, much of any AI-driven productivity gains will only inflate land. It is likely that much of Australia’s social cohesion issues [are housing related](https://www.anu.edu.au/news/all-news/cost-of-living-pressures-sees-social-cohesion-hit-record-low).

Housing reform is AI policy.

## Trade Structure

AI may shift value away from certain forms of labour-intensive production and toward energy, materials, and capital-intensive sectors. Australia’s exposure to critical minerals and energy could be a structural advantage — if supply constraints do not choke development.

## Obsolescence of Current Digital Infrastructure

[AI agents do not use the internet the way humans do](https://spectrum.ieee.org/ai-agent-economy).

If individuals can delegate search, comparison, and filtering to AI systems, much of the current ad-supported interface layer of the internet becomes less valuable. Platforms built around capturing human attention may find that their economic model erodes when AI intermediates interaction.

The problem isn't just advertising, either. My AI bot can ignore your limited search UI and laboriously retrieve as many pages as it needs to satisfy whatever idiosyncratic request I have. The worse your search experience, the more it will cost you in an explosion of page retrievals. This problem will is about to hit almost all commerce sites *hard*.

This possibility is largely ignored in mainstream discussion, but it has serious implications for capital allocation and digital business models.

## Firm Structure and Market Concentration

On the one hand, AI allows large firms to:
- [Increase returns to scale](https://www.goldmansachs.com/insights/articles/ai-may-favor-big-tech-incumbents) (large models, data advantages, compute access);
- Reduce [internal](https://ascelibrary.org/doi/abs/10.1061/JMENEA.MEENG-7079) and [external](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1059056025007609) coordination costs ; and
- Lower the cost of managing complexity.

On the other hand, small firms will be able to [get good tax, management, investment, legal and other advice without having to become large firms](https://andeglobal.org/ai-is-moving-fast-small-businesses-cant-be-left-behind/).

For Australia, this matters because:
- We are already a small, oligopolistic economy.
- Increased scale economies globally may entrench imported dominance (US tech giants).
- Domestic competition policy may need to adapt.

The second-order effect here is not unemployment — it is market power and industrial structure.

## Shifts in Bargaining Power

Even without large unemployment, AI may shift bargaining power between:
- Capital and labour,
- Senior and junior employees,
- Firms and contractors.

If junior white-collar work becomes automatable, career ladders compress. That could:
- Increase inequality within occupations,
- Alter human capital investment incentives,
- Change migration patterns (e.g., fewer entry-level skilled visas).

This is a subtle but powerful structural shift.

## Financial Market and Asset Price Effects

Second order financial effects can be very important:
- Revaluation of advertising-dependent platforms;
- Rising valuations for energy, transmission, and data infrastructure;
- Increased volatility from AI investment cycles; and
- Higher correlation between tech and energy sectors.

Australia’s superannuation system is deeply exposed to global equities. If AI shifts global asset pricing materially, it affects retirement savings and domestic financial stability.f

## Migration Policy Feedback

Australia has unusually flexible migration settings.

If AI:
- Substitutes for some skilled migrants,
- Increases demand for others (energy engineers, data specialists),
- Reduces need for certain offshore service roles,

Then migration composition may shift significantly.

That has second-order effects on:
- Housing demand,
- Wage growth,
- Political dynamics.

## International Trade and Geopolitics

AI could reshape comparative advantage.

If AI lowers the importance of labour cost differentials:
- Manufacturing may partially re-shore in high-income countries; and
- Value may shift toward capital, energy, and resource inputs.

Australia’s strength in:
- Critical minerals;
- LNG; and
- Agricultural optimisation

could become more valuable — or more geopolitically contested.

## Education Transformation

AI tutoring and assessment tools could:
- Lower cost of high-quality instruction;
- Change university business models; and
- Reduce value of some credential pathways.

Australia has a large export education sector.

If AI reduces the premium on certain types of degrees, what happens to the university revenue model?

## Measurement Problems

If AI dramatically increases consumer surplus in ways not captured by GDP:
- Official productivity statistics may understate real gains.
- Policy may overreact to perceived stagnation.
- Real wage statistics may diverge from lived experience.

Mis-measurement can distort fiscal and monetary policy decisions.

## Government Capacity Improvements

Much of what government provides is services. If service efficiency improves dramatically — and government policy is able to express these improvements effectively — then:

- Fiscal pressures ease;
- State capacity increases; and
- Policy iteration accelerates.

On the other hand, if private sector improvements greatly outpace government efficiency, general dissatisfaction with government will rise along with domestic political tension.

Government efficiency is closely related to perhaps the most crucial near-term policy issue: housing.

